INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (585, 'Good morning.
Vaginitis is a term used to describe vaginal inflammation or infection, characterised by itching, foul-smelling discharge and sometimes, pain. Number of factors have been known to cause this, and these include imbalance in vaginal normal flora, bacterial infection and oestrogen depletion in post menopausal women.
The vagina has its own resident microorganisms (normal flora) which perform protective roles in the vagina. Once these organisms are depleted due to some unhealthy practices like douching (washing inside of the vagina with soap), usage of vaginal spray, etc...other harmful bacteria can then begin to multiply in the vagina, leading to infection.
These bacteria can also invade the vagina in cases relating to immunosuppression.
It is advisable that any female with symptoms of vaginitis visit a doctor, who can further examine and run some tests to know the exact organisms implicated, and as such prescribe the appropriate medication to CURE the condition.
Thank you.', 336, 287, 0, null, 0, '2019-07-23 06:45:04', '2019-07-23 06:45:04', null);
INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (586, 'Hi.
I''m sorry about the stress you''ve had so far, with contraceptives.
Hormonal contraceptives can cause weight gain and progesterone-only implants are notorious for causing menstrual irregularities.
If you use combined oral contraceptives, your menstrual cycle will be regular but you may still gain weight. Also note that you have to take the pills everyday at a regular time.
You could also use a non-hormonal intrauterine contraceptive device like Copper IUCD, which won''t make you gain weight or cause menstrual irregularities, but it may cause heavy menstrual flow.
There are barrier methods that you could use too, in form of female condom or cervical cap. You could also use spermicidal creams.
Kindly visit the family planning clinic for any of these options that will be suitable for you.
