INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (703, 'Hi, 

There’s no point living in fear of something that you have control over, so long as you completed your dosage and are taking precautions, then I believe you should not have to worry about that. 

However, here are some precautions to take to  reduce your chances of a reoccurrence of pelvic inflammatory disease; 

1. Practice safe sex. Use condoms every time you have sex, limit your number of partners, and always ask about a potential partner''s sexual history.
2. Get regularly tested for STIs. If you''re at risk of an STI, such as chlamydia, make an appointment with your doctor for testing. Set up a regular screening schedule with your doctor if needed. Early treatment of an STI gives you the best chance of avoiding PID.
3. Request that your partner be tested. If you have pelvic inflammatory disease or an STI, advise your partner to be tested and, if necessary, treated. This can prevent the spread of STIs and possible recurrence of PID.
4. Don''t douche. Douching upsets the balance of protective bacteria in your vagina.
5. Temporary abstinence. Avoid sexual intercourse until treatment is completed and tests indicate that the infection has cleared in all partner(s).

Here’s to a hopeful PID-free existence! All the best', 13, 352, 0, null, 0, '2019-08-03 16:49:37', '2019-08-03 16:49:37', null);
