INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (721, 'Hi, 

Headaches, fever and running stomach are a rather vague set of symptoms become of how common they occur. Are there other associated symptoms? Does the cluster characteristics of the headache occur with fever and running stomach at the same time? Is there abdominal pain, nausea and/or vomiting? 
Depending on the answers, you might have food poisoning, an underlying infection, or migraines. 

My advice is to visit a doctor who will be able to rule out the causes and proffer treatment. 

However, here is a short info on what cluster headache is;

It often awakens you in the middle of the night with intense pain in or around one eye/ one side of your head and the pain most times ends as suddenly as it started. Usually leaving you exhausted after the headache. 
They are referred to as “cluster headache” because there are bouts of attacks that occur with a period, this is know as a cluster period.  It can lasts for up to months and then followed by remission periods when there are no attacks. 

If you suffer cluster headaches you may experience the following; a sudden onset that lasts for between 15 minutes to three hours, often occurs at the same time each day and mostly at night. Described as an excruciating pain that is generally situated around ONE eye, but may radiate to other areas of your face, head and neck, one-sided pain with excessive tearing and associated restlessness. 
Some people complain of sensitivity to light and sound. 

