INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (1055, 'Hello, 

It is possible that you might have had an incomplete miscarriage. 
In situations like this, the scan will show an empty uterus with no signs of pregnancy but the urine/blood tests will still be positive for a few days after. 
Pregnancy tests detect the presence of the pregnancy hormone hCG, however, after a miscarriage occurs, the hormone does not disappear from a woman''s body right away, instead the level of hCG gradually decreases, falling back down to an undetectable level over a period of days, or even weeks, depending on how far along the pregnancy was when the miscarriage happened.

With an incomplete miscarriage, there is still pregnancy tissue leftover in the uterus, but unfortunately, it does not mean that the pregnancy is continuing or is viable. Symptoms are complaints of passage of clots or pieces of tissue plus vaginal bleeding with associated cramps.

A  simple medical procedure might be required to remove the retained products of conception, which is usually only small pieces of the placenta. These tissues will probably be reabsorbed (broken down) by your body in time, but the procedure can help put a stop to heavy bleeding sooner, as bleeding is a common symptom of an incomplete miscarriage.

Please visit a gynaecologist for review and proper management, should this be this case! 

All the best.', 13, 572, 0, null, 0, '2019-09-21 20:36:34', '2019-09-21 20:36:34', null);
INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (1056, 'Congratulations! At 39 weeks pregnant, you''ve got a full-term baby. Anytime between week 38 and 40 is usually ideal for delivery. 

