INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (1376, 'Firstly,pregnancy is not an  absolute contraindication to dental treatment.
Only that  it is safe to delay elective dental treaments  until after delivery,in women still  in their  1st  or  3rd trimesters.This is because of a  couple of factors viz:The risk of  exposure of the  foetus  in the first trimester of pregnancy to radiation from dental xray and also, the risk of orthostatic hypotension hence the resultant  syncope that is likely to  happen when a  heavily  pregnant woman sits on the dental chair for  long while undergoing dental treatment.
However,while  dentists would take adequate measures to reduce these risks, dental treatment could still be done during pregnancy(depending on the severity  of the patient''s symptoms and also, depending on  whether the said treament is invasive or noninvasive).
As for the  dental treatments which might warrant postponement until after delivery,such treatments can be done anytime after delivery as long as  the woman has been certified fit by her doctors to go home.
Even though there is no time frame,a dentist could decide to wait for three months depending on the emotional readiness of the patient and other patient- based factors.
However to the best of my knowledge  there  is no evidence from research  stating any benefit  to waiting for 3months  post delivery,before initiating dental treatment.', 15, 806, 0, null, 0, '2019-11-19 23:01:20', '2019-11-19 23:01:20', null);
