INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (1781, 'Hello Anonymous, I’m really sorry about your loss and congratulations on conceiving again. 
There are a number of requirements before one qualifies for a VBAC. First of all, the reason for the first CS should not be a recurrent one. For instance, if the reason for the first CS was a small pelvis, there’s no point trying for a VBAC. 
The duration between the date of your last CS and the date of conception of this pregnancy should not be less than 15 months because this increases the risk of a ruptured uterus. 
Following your CS if there was any infection of the womb or of the wound, it reduces the quality of the CS scar and a repeat CS would be advisable. 
At 36 weeks of pregnancy, your doctor will ask you to do a scan to measure baby’s weight and thickness of the CS Scar, An X-ray or CT Scan of the pelvis will also be done to see if it is adequate. If all these parameters are okay you can then be scheduled for a VBAC. 
It is important to note that in most centers, you will be given a grace till 41weeks and 3 days to come in natural labor because induction of labor is not done routinely in women with previous CS. 
I hope this helps.', 1732, 1104, 0, null, 0, '2020-03-22 14:38:57', '2020-03-22 14:38:57', null);
INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (1782, 'Congratulations for the gift of God on the way. 

First thing I would advise you do is get a good Obstetrician to manage this pregnancy. 

There are so many reasons surrounding the successful delivery after Caeserian section. 
‘’what was the reason for the first emergency CS; was the leading twin breech, a preterm contraction, preterm rupture of membrane, or a planned CS due to it being a precious baby as you have said?’’ If none of the reasons are recurring and there’s no cause for you to have CS this time around, then you have a chance of going for VBAC.

Also, the timing for VBAC also depends on many factors. 
If your last delivery is a year ago and you are just pregnant now, meaning you’ve got about 20-21 months to the time of delivery, you can go for a trial of VBAC if your Obstetrician agrees to it. I hope this helps. Congratulations once again.', 1255, 1104, 0, null, 0, '2020-03-22 14:41:10', '2020-03-22 14:41:10', null);
