INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (2021, 'Hello, thank you for using Wellvis.
Body odour occurs from the action of part of the body’s normal flora on sweat. Body odour is common and may be associated with excessive sweating. Things that can make body odour worse include poor personal hygiene, exercise, hot weather, being overweight, hormonal changes, certain medications and the presence of medical conditions like diabetes, liver and kidney disease.

Some tips include the following: 
Have your bathe at least twice daily, increase the frequency if you have been involved in particularly rigorous activity. 
Pay attention to your armpit, groin and feet and be sure to towel-dry thoroughly. Take a shower after exercising. 
Shave your armpit regularly. 
Change and wash your clothes regularly. 
Reduce intake of certain foods that have strong smells like garlic, onion, curry as their intake might increase body odour that results from some of your sweat glands. Also, reduce the intake of caffeine and alcohol-containing drinks as they might contribute to body odour.
Maintain a healthy weight for your height. 
Use deodorants.
You will need to visit a hospital if the symptoms don’t resolve despite doing all the above, if you notice a change in how it usually smells or if you suddenly begin to sweat much more than usual.
