INSERT INTO ebdb.thread_comments (id, content, user_id, thread_id, is_retrieved, retrieved_at, is_answer, created_at, updated_at, deleted_at) VALUES (2506, 'Hello there and thanks for using Wellvis

It is not uncommon to see babies with their (umbilical) cord wrapped around their necks. It is not as a result of any cause from the mother and usually does not cause any harm during delivery. It is sometimes but not always associated with excess amniotic fluid or when there is more than one baby in the womb. It is usually loosely wrapped around the neck allowing normal foetal blood flow. 

If detected early, it is not a cause for concern as long as the baby movements can still be felt throughout the pregnancy. During labour, the heart rate and vitals of the baby will be monitored as usual to detect any distress and act accordingly. If it is a normal delivery with the head coming out first, one of things always checked for is if the cord is around the neck. This will be removed first before delivering the rest of the baby''s body.

So it''s important to regular at and report any changes during antenatal visits, as well as making sure delivery occurs in a health facility from skilled hands.

